de and disputes over protection. In our increasingly technological world, maritime piracy represents not only an interruption, but an attempt to insert oneself within the world of oceanic trade. Captured at Sea moves beyond the binaries of legal and illegal to illustrate how the seas continue to be key sites of global regulation, connectivity, and commerce today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aHijacking of shipszSomaliay21st century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  abarrels of crude oil.  abook about somalian pirates.  abook three in series.  acoast of somalia.  aexploration of maritime piracy.  ainsurance offices in london.  aliberian flagged oil tanker hostage.  amodern day pirates.  anegotiate pay out.  aonboard multinational container ships.  apirate communities in somalia.  areturn of crew.  aseas key sites of global regulation.  aseries.  asix men.  asomalian pirates.  atrade and disputes over protection.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Economics, Law & Social Sciences 2019 ENGz978311061013008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2019z9783110606485oZDB-23-DSW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCA Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065207908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311066763940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520973299zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520973299423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520973299.jpg 